<TITLE> Turkish minister says free speech amendment ready </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ISTANBUL, Jan 21 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Turkey's government will submit to parliament in the next few days a plan to amend a controversial law that restricts freedom of speech, Justice Minister Mehmet Ali Sahin was quoted on Monday as saying. Sahin told the Sabah newspaper the government hoped the amendment, long sought by the European Union which Ankara aims to join, would be approved by the end of the month. "The text is ready. Within a few days the amendment will be handed to the speaker of parliament. We plan to make it law by the end of the month," Sahin told Sabah in an interview. Turkey has been under heavy pressure from the EU and rights groups to amend article 301 of the penal code, which makes "insulting Turkishness" a crime and has been used to prosecute dozens of writers, including Nobel laureate Orhan Pamuk. The ruling AK Party has repeatedly promised to alter the law but Turkish media say conservatives within the government have been blocking Sahin's plans. The amendment is expected to substitute "Turkish nation" for the vaguer "Turkishness" and may require prosecutors to win the permission of the Justice Ministry or a special panel of experts before being able to launch a case under the article. EU Enlargement Commissioner Olli Rehn has recommended that the bloc not extend accession talks with Turkey to the key areas of justice and home affairs until the article is changed. The European Commission's annual progress report on Turkey, published in November, urged Ankara to make "significant further efforts" on freedom of expression, noting that more people had been prosecuted under article 301 last year than in 20
